      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Strategy for Gore</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Carol Feit Lane letter comments on Frank Rich's Oct 21 Op-Ed column on problems with Vice Pres Al Gore's presidential campaign</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Frank Rich aptly articulates some of the problems with Al Gore's campaign (column, Oct. 21). But it's not too late for the vice president to let the country know that he is the man we need.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Frank Rich aptly articulates some of the problems with Al Gore's campaign (column, Oct. 21). But it's not too late for the vice president to let the country know that he is the man we need.</p>
        <p>First, Mr. Gore must re-connect with President Clinton and show that he is aligned with all that is good about the administration. This is not in conflict with ''being one's own man.'' He needs to emphasize that he will continue the popular policies of the Clinton administration, which have led to the prosperity and well-being of the last eight years.</p>
        <p>Second, Mr. Gore can let Mr. Clinton help deliver the message that we should not ''change horses in mid-stream,'' especially in view of the crisis in the Middle East.</p>
        <p>Also, there are critical issues at stake for our economy and major decisions to be made, like the selection of Supreme Court justices, that will affect our lives for decades.</p>
        <p>CAROL FEIT LANE  New York, Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
